{"title_page": "Borkou (region of Chad)", "text_new": "{{redirects|Borkou (region)|for the historical region|Borkou}}\n{{coord|17.9167|N|19.1167|E|type:adm1st_source:itwiki|display=title}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Borkou\n| native_name             = \u0628\u0631\u0643\u0648\n| native_name_lang        = ar<!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type         = [[Regions of Chad|Region]]\n| image_skyline           =Emi Koussi inner crater.jpg \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           =Inner crater of Emi Koussi, highest mountain in Chad, located in Borkou \n| image_flag              = \n| flag_alt                = \n| image_seal              = \n| seal_alt                = \n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = \n| image_map               = Map of Borkou Region.png\n| mapsize                 = 200px\n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = Map of Chad showing the Borkou region\n| pushpin_map             = \n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| latd  =  \n|latm  =  \n|lats  =  \n|latNS  = \n| longd =  \n|longm =  \n|longs =  \n|longEW = \n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Chad]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Departments of Chad|Departments]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Sub-prefectures of Chad|Sub-prefectures]]\n| subdivision_type3       = \n| subdivision_name1       = 2\n| subdivision_name2       = 4\n| subdivision_name3       = \n| established_title       = Region\n| established_date        = 2012\n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = [[Capital city|Capital]]\n| seat                    = [[Faya-Largeau]]\n| government_footnotes    = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = Metric<!-- or US or UK -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_land_km2           = \n| area_water_km2          = \n| area_water_percent      = \n| area_note               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 97,251\n| population_as_of        = 2009\n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_note         = \n| timezone1               = \n| utc_offset1             = \n| timezone1_DST           = \n| utc_offset1_DST         = \n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code               = \n| area_code_type          = \n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\nThe '''Borkou region''' ({{lang-ar|\u0628\u0631\u0643\u0648}}) is a [[regions of Chad|region]] of [[Chad]] which was created in 2008 from the [[Borkou Department|Borkou department]] of the former [[Borkou-Ennedi-Tibesti Region|Borkou-Ennedi-Tibesti region]]. Its capital is [[Faya-Largeau]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe region borders [[Libya]] to the north, [[Ennedi-Ouest Region]] to the east, [[Wadi Fira Region]], [[Batha Region]], [[Bahr el Gazel (region of Chad)|Bahr el Gazel Region]] and [[Kanem Region]] to the south, and [[Niger]] and [[Tibesti Region]] the west. Borkou is located in the [[Sahara Desert]], and contains parts of the [[Tibesti Mountains]] in its north. The highest point in [[Chad]], [[Emi Koussi]], is located in Borkou.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Borkou|title=Borkou {{!}} region, Chad|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe region's northern border lies within the [[Aouzou Strip]], historically a point of dispute between [[Chad]] and [[Libya]].<ref name=\"West Pg. 57\">Geoffrey Leslie Simons, ''Libya and the West: from independence to Lockerbie'', Centre for Libyan Studies (Oxford, England). Pg. 57</ref>\n\n===Settlements===\n[[Faya-Largeau]] is the regional capital; other major settlements include [[Gouro, Chad|Gouro]], [[Kirdimi]], [[Koro Toro]] and [[Yarda, Chad|Yarda]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://reliefweb.int/map/chad/tchad-r%C3%A9gion-du-borkou-juin-2010| title = Tchad : R\u00e9gion du Borkou - Juin 2010 | format = [[PDF]] | publisher = [[UNOCHA]] | accessdate = 4 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAs per the census of 2009, the population of the region was 97,251, 46.6% female. The average size of household as of 2009 is 6.00: 6.00 in rural households and 5.80 in urban areas. The total number of households was 16,191: 10,584 in rural areas and 5,607 in urban areas. The number of nomads in the region was 8,221, 2.1% of the population. There were 96,459 people residing in private households. There were 47,285 above 18 years of ages: 24,775 male and 22,510 female. The sex ratio was 114.00 females for every hundred males. There were 89,030 sedentary staff, 0.80 of the total population.<ref name=census>{{cite web|title=Census of Chad|url=http://chad.opendataforafrica.org/areounf/census-of-population-and-housing-chad-2009|year=2009|publisher=National Institute of Statistical, Economic and Demographic Studies, Chad|accessdate=17 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121042557/http://chad.opendataforafrica.org/areounf/census-of-population-and-housing-chad-2009|archivedate=21 November 2016}}</ref> The [[Dazaga]] and [[Tedaga]] [[Toubou people|Toubou]] are the dominant ethnic group in the region.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ethnologue.com/country/TD/languages| title = Languages of Chad | publisher = [[Ethnologue]] | accessdate = 27 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Administration==\nAs a part of decentralisation in February 2003, the country is administratively split into regions, departments, municipalities and rural communities. The prefectures which were originally 14 in number were re-designated in 17 regions. The regions are administered by Governors appointed by the President. The Prefects, who originally held the responsibility of the 14 prefects, still retained the titles and were responsible for the administration of smaller departments in each region. The members of local assemblies are elected every six years, while the executive organs are elected every three years.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://unpan1.un.org/intradoc/groups/public/documents/un/unpan023258.pdf|page=9|title=Republic of Chad Public Administration and Country profile|format=PDF|accessdate=17 November 2016|publisher=Department of Economic and Social Affairs (DESA), United Nations|year=2004}}</ref> As of 2016, there are totally 23 regions in Chad, which are divided based on population and administrative convenience. The Borkou region is divided into two [[Departments of Chad|departments]], namely, [[Borkou Department|Borkou]] (capital [[Faya-Largeau]]) and [[Borkou Yala]] (capital [[Kirdimi]], also called Kirdi).<ref>{{cite report|title=Chad district map|url=https://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/chad.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=20 November 2016|publisher=Department of Field Support,Cartographic Section, United Nations}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n{{Regions of Chad}}\n\n[[Category:Borkou Region| ]]\n[[Category:Regions of Chad]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirects|Borkou (region)|for the historical region|Borkou}}\n{{coord|17.9167|N|19.1167|E|type:adm1st_source:itwiki|display=title}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Borkou\n| native_name             = \u0628\u0631\u0643\u0648\n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type         = [[Regions of Chad|Region]]\n| image_skyline           =Emi Koussi inner crater.jpg \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           =Inner crater of Emi Koussi, highest mountain in Chad, located in Borkou \n| image_flag              = \n| flag_alt                = \n| image_seal              = \n| seal_alt                = \n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = \n| image_map               = Map of Borkou Region.png\n| mapsize                 = 200px\n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = Map of Chad showing the Borkou region\n| pushpin_map             = \n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| latd  =  \n|latm  =  \n|lats  =  \n|latNS  = \n| longd =  \n|longm =  \n|longs =  \n|longEW = \n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Chad]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Departments of Chad|Departments]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Sub-prefectures of Chad|Sub-prefectures]]\n| subdivision_type3       = \n| subdivision_name1       = 2\n| subdivision_name2       = 4\n| subdivision_name3       = \n| established_title       = Region\n| established_date        = 2012\n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = [[Capital city|Capital]]\n| seat                    = [[Faya-Largeau]]\n| government_footnotes    = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = Metric<!-- or US or UK -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_land_km2           = \n| area_water_km2          = \n| area_water_percent      = \n| area_note               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 97,251\n| population_as_of        = 2009\n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_note         = \n| timezone1               = \n| utc_offset1             = \n| timezone1_DST           = \n| utc_offset1_DST         = \n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code               = \n| area_code_type          = \n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\nThe '''Borkou region''' ({{lang-ar|\u0628\u0631\u0643\u0648}}) is a [[regions of Chad|region]] of [[Chad]] which was created in 2008 from the [[Borkou Department|Borkou department]] of the former [[Borkou-Ennedi-Tibesti Region|Borkou-Ennedi-Tibesti region]]. Its capital is [[Faya-Largeau]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe region borders [[Libya]] to the north, [[Ennedi-Ouest Region]] to the east, [[Wadi Fira Region]], [[Batha Region]], [[Bahr el Gazel (region of Chad)|Bahr el Gazel Region]] and [[Kanem Region]] to the south, and [[Niger]] and [[Tibesti Region]] the west. Borkou is located in the [[Sahara Desert]], and contains parts of the [[Tibesti Mountains]] in its north. The highest point in [[Chad]], [[Emi Koussi]], is located in Borkou.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Borkou|title=Borkou {{!}} region, Chad|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe region's northern border lies within the [[Aouzou Strip]], historically a point of dispute between [[Chad]] and [[Libya]].<ref name=\"West Pg. 57\">Geoffrey Leslie Simons, ''Libya and the West: from independence to Lockerbie'', Centre for Libyan Studies (Oxford, England). Pg. 57</ref>\n\n===Settlements===\n[[Faya-Largeau]] is the regional capital; other major settlements include [[Gouro, Chad|Gouro]], [[Kirdimi]], [[Koro Toro]] and [[Yarda, Chad|Yarda]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://reliefweb.int/map/chad/tchad-r%C3%A9gion-du-borkou-juin-2010| title = Tchad : R\u00e9gion du Borkou - Juin 2010 | format = [[PDF]] | publisher = [[UNOCHA]] | accessdate = 4 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAs per the census of 2009, the population of the region was 97,251, 46.6% female. The average size of household as of 2009 is 6.00: 6.00 in rural households and 5.80 in urban areas. The total number of households was 16,191: 10,584 in rural areas and 5,607 in urban areas. The number of nomads in the region was 8,221, 2.1% of the population. There were 96,459 people residing in private households. There were 47,285 above 18 years of ages: 24,775 male and 22,510 female. The sex ratio was 114.00 females for every hundred males. There were 89,030 sedentary staff, 0.80 of the total population.<ref name=census>{{cite web|title=Census of Chad|url=http://chad.opendataforafrica.org/areounf/census-of-population-and-housing-chad-2009|year=2009|publisher=National Institute of Statistical, Economic and Demographic Studies, Chad|accessdate=17 November 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121042557/http://chad.opendataforafrica.org/areounf/census-of-population-and-housing-chad-2009|archivedate=21 November 2016}}</ref> The [[Dazaga]] and [[Tedaga]] [[Toubou people|Toubou]] are the dominant ethnic group in the region.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ethnologue.com/country/TD/languages| title = Languages of Chad | publisher = [[Ethnologue]] | accessdate = 27 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Administration==\nAs a part of decentralisation in February 2003, the country is administratively split into regions, departments, municipalities and rural communities. The prefectures which were originally 14 in number were re-designated in 17 regions. The regions are administered by Governors appointed by the President. The Prefects, who originally held the responsibility of the 14 prefects, still retained the titles and were responsible for the administration of smaller departments in each region. The members of local assemblies are elected every six years, while the executive organs are elected every three years.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://unpan1.un.org/intradoc/groups/public/documents/un/unpan023258.pdf|page=9|title=Republic of Chad Public Administration and Country profile|format=PDF|accessdate=17 November 2016|publisher=Department of Economic and Social Affairs (DESA), United Nations|year=2004}}</ref> As of 2016, there are totally 23 regions in Chad, which are divided based on population and administrative convenience. The Borkou region is divided into two [[Departments of Chad|departments]], namely, [[Borkou Department|Borkou]] (capital [[Faya-Largeau]]) and [[Borkou Yala]] (capital [[Kirdimi]], also called Kirdi).<ref>{{cite report|title=Chad district map|url=https://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/chad.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=20 November 2016|publisher=Department of Field Support,Cartographic Section, United Nations}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n{{Regions of Chad}}\n\n[[Category:Borkou Region| ]]\n[[Category:Regions of Chad]]\n", "name_user": "Sinaloa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Borkou_(region_of_Chad)"}
